Process ID: 74829 - LIGHT OLEFINS UNIT (LOU)



The Light Olefins Unit (LOU) Process has five units which are the Hot Side, Cold Side, GHU/PHU, PDU and LOU Offsites. The Hot Side includes the furnaces up through the quench columns. The Cold Side includes compression, refrigeration, and fractionation. GHU/PHU are two stage gasoline and pyrolysis gasoline hydrogenation units. The PDU is the propylene drying and transfer units. LOU Offsites include tankage, waste water stripping unit, flare, custody transfer stations, and loading racks associated with the LOU. The process controls, mitigations, monitors and detectors listed apply to all units except as follows: the PDU and LOU Offsites do not have automatic shutoffs; the GHU/PHU and Cold Side are the only units with quench system process controls; only LOU Offsite unit tankage have dikes; the GHU and part of the PHU do not have process area detectors; and fire detectors are only at the PDU, LOU, Compressor Decks, and LOU Lube Oil Skids. The flammable mixture mass noted below includes inventories of non RMP flammable chemicals and RMP flammable chemicals below the threshold quantity in the process. RMP chemicals below the threshold quantity included in the flammable mixture are: Acetylene, Ethyl Acetylene, cylohexlamine, Vinyl acetate, Hydrogen Sulfide, Carbon Disulfide, and Hydrogen.









Operations comply with OSHA Standard 29 CFR 1910.119, Process Safety Management of highly hazardous chemicals via Corporate and Local management?s commitment to the elements of PSM by applying the programs and policies found in the standard to activities throughout the facility. Specific program elements include:

1. Employee Participation ? It is the policy of Flint Hills Resources (FHR) to seek participation of employees at all levels in establishing procedures and practices that govern Health, Safety and Environmental issues.  The PSM Policy includes a description of how the Employee Participation element is implemented in 11.3-1; 

2. Process Safety Information ? Process safety information is maintained for the facility.  The PSM Policy includes a description of how the Process Safety Information element is implemented in 11.3-2; 

3. Process Hazard Analysis ? A detailed process hazard assessment, using HAZOP, is conducted on the facility to insure that it has been designed safely.  The PSM   Policy includes a description of how the Process Hazard Analysis element is implemented in 11.3-3; 

4. Operating Procedures ? A system is in place to ensure that updated and approved procedures cover the facility's operation.  The PSM Policy includes a description of how the Operating Procedure element is implemented in 11.3-4; 

5. Training ? A training program has been established to ensure that personnel are well trained in the specific duties of their jobs (The process also includes an annual Training Needs Analysis).  The PSM Policy includes a description of how the Training element is implemented in 11.3-5; 

6. Contractors ? It is FHR's objective to partner with contractors that share the same safety philosophy.  A dedicated, collective, and consistent approach by FHR and contractors will enhance and maintain the safety and health of our respective employees.  The PSM Contractor Management Program element is included in R-01 Contractor EHS Procedure; 

7. Prestart up Safety Review ? A prestart up safety review walk down and checklist is completed for changes that impact the Process Safety Information. P-01 Management of Change Procedure includes a description of how the Prestart up Safety Review element is implemented; 

8. Mechanical Integrity ? An equipment inspection program is in place to ensure equipment remains in good condition to prevent releases.  The PSM Policy  includes a description of how the Mechanical Integrity element is implemented in 11.3-4; 

9. Hot Work Permits ? A work permit system is in place to ensure that work on process equipment and hot work are conducted in a safe manner.  The PSM Policy and includes a description of how the Hot Work element is implemented in 11.3-9.  Site procedure MOLPU-004 covers hot work permitting at the rail facility; 

10. Management of Change ? A management of change system has been established and implemented to ensure that changes are thoroughly reviewed prior to implementation.  P-01 Management of Change Procedure includes a description of how the Management of Change element is implemented; 

11. Incident Investigation ? Incidents are investigated using one of several industry recognized methodologies, such as Tap Root, to determine system level root causes that can be remedied to prevent a reoccurrence. Employees and contractors involved in the incident are included on the investigation team.  The PSM Policy includes a description of how the Incident Investigation element is implemented in 11.3-11; 

12. Emergency Planning and Response ? An emergency action plan has been established.  The ICP Plan includes a description of how the Emergency Planning and Response element is implemented; 

13. Compliance Audits ? Programs are evaluated annually; audited at least every three years through PSM compliance audits; and weekly safety inspections of the facility are conducted by cross functional teams.  Action items resulting from these are tracked to a timely completion.  The PSM Policy includes a description of how the Compliance Audit element is implemented in 11.3-13; 

14. Trade Secrets ? There are no Trade Secret issues at this facility, per se. This is covered in 11.3-14 of the PSM Policy.

Process ID: 74830 - AU/CYCLOHEXANE UNIT



The AU/Cyclohexane Process has three units: UDEX, Cyclohexane and AU/Cyclohexane Offsites. The UDEX is an aromatics separations unit. The Cyclohexane Unit manufactures cyclohexane. The AU/Cyclohexane Offsites includes storage, cooling tower, and flare. The risk management program's elements for the units listed apply to all units except as follows: Only the Cyclohexane unit has a quench system; the dikes apply only to storage tanks in the AU/Cyclohexane Unit. The emergency power and air, automatic shutoffs and purge system do not apply to the AU/Cyclohexane Offsites Unit. The flammable mixture mass noted below includes inventories of non RMP flammable chemicals and RMP flammable chemicals below the threshold quantity in the process. RMP chemicals below the threshold quantity included in the flammable mixture are: 1,3 Butadiene; 2-Pentene, (E); 2-Methyl-1-Butene; 2-Pentene (Z); 2 Butene-cis; Butane; Ethane; Isobutane; Methane; Propane, 1-Pentene, Vinyl acetate, and Hydrogen.





